x4freetext: Water-cooled Ti-N targets, 6 keV
thick at Ep=0.5 MeV.
72 cm3 detector. Data taken at 45 degrees.
Proton beams were supplied by the 0.6 and 2.6
MV electrostatic accelerators at the Kellogg
Radiation Laboratory. The targets were able to
withstand bombardment with beam currents of 70 microA
for periods greater than 5 days without noticeable
deterioration . The gamma-rays have been observed
with Ge(Li) detector.

The astrophysical S-factors were extracted from
energy-dependent experimental cross sections through
the relation: S(E) = sigma(E) Ecm exp[2 pi eta(cm)],
where eta(cm) is the usual Coulomb parameter at the
projectile energy in the c.m. system.
